# Browser Security Review Context (iOS & macOS)

> **Purpose:** This document provides security context for incremental code reviews of **DuckDuckGo for iOS and macOS** in this repository. It encodes the threat model, known vulnerability classes, risk assessment methodology, and **WebKit / WKWebView** attack surfaces derived from the Special Pages Security Assessment. **Windows, Android, and web extensions are out of scope** for this document.

## How to use this document

1. **Pair with** [security-agent-instructions.mdc](./security-agent-instructions.mdc) — that file defines **silence-by-default** behavior, PR comment format, and when path triggers imply *review* vs. *mandatory comments*.
2. **Reporting threshold:** Emit a finding only when you can state (a) which trust boundary from Section 1 is at risk, (b) a plausible attacker path from Section 6, and (c) severity at least Medium per Section 2 (or a clear regression from Section 10). Otherwise respond that there is no material issue for this threat model.
3. **Section 7** is for structured verification; do not dump the entire checklist into PR comments (see `security-agent-instructions.mdc`).

---

## 1. Architecture Overview

The iOS and macOS apps embed **WKWebView** and implement **special pages** — internal browser pages served via the `duck://` custom URI scheme (e.g., `duck://history`, `duck://newtab`, `duck://onboarding`, `duck://settings`).

Special pages communicate with native code through **message handlers** — a bridge between JavaScript in the WebView and the native layer via `window.webkit.messageHandlers`.

### Trust Boundaries

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  UNTRUSTED: Web Content (any origin)                │
│  ┌───────────────────────────────────────────────┐  │
│  │  SEMI-TRUSTED: duckduckgo.com origins         │  │
│  │  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐  │  │
│  │  │  TRUSTED: duck:// special pages          │  │  │
│  │  │  ┌───────────────────────────────────┐   │  │  │
│  │  │  │  PRIVILEGED: Native bridge layer  │   │  │  │
│  │  │  └───────────────────────────────────┘   │  │  │
│  │  └─────────────────────────────────────────┘  │  │
│  └───────────────────────────────────────────────┘  │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

The critical invariant: **untrusted web content must never be able to invoke privileged native operations.** Every finding in this assessment traces back to a violation or weakening of this boundary.

