## 2. Vulnerability Classification

Severity levels for native app vulnerabilities:

### Critical

- Arbitrary remote code execution
- Password manager compromise
- Arbitrary local file access

### High

- Privacy-compromising issues:
  - Inappropriate cookie access
  - Leaking usernames, Duck addresses, or email addresses from autofill/password manager
  - Limited local file access
  - Unauthorized location access
  - Leaking true IP address while connected to VPN
  - Disclosure of browser history
  - Disclosure of authentication tokens
- Universal XSS
- Same-Origin Policy (SOP) bypass / cross-site information leakage
- Sandbox escape

### Medium

- Detection of arbitrary local files
- TLS certificate mishandling (accepting untrusted/expired/insecure certs, inaccurate security indicators, HSTS bypass)
- Launching local applications
- UI redressing and address spoofing

### Low

- CSP bypass
- Site permissions bypass

### Out of Scope

- Local attacks (requiring physical access)
- Application crashes (unless exploitable)
- Social engineering
- Lack of binary protections

### Severity Adjustment Factors

Severity may be adjusted (typically by one level) based on:

**Increases severity:**

- No user interaction required (navigate-to-URL-only attacks)
- Actively exploited or PoC code published
- Large number of affected users/websites

**Decreases severity:**

- Requires non-default settings or additional installed software
- Requires user to have granted specific permissions
- Only applies to misconfigured sites
- Involves non-reproducible race conditions
- Requires multiple clicks or timing

